The script uses timestamp-based throttling to prevent performance issues. It checks the time elapsed since the last sparkle spawn using `Date.now()`. If less than 40ms have passed, the function returns early. This ensures sparkles are only created every 40ms, preventing excessive DOM node generation that could melt the GPU. Example code:
javascript
var now = Date.now();
if (now - lastSparkleTime < 40) return;
lastSparkleTime = now;

To simulate a walking pixel cat with vertical bounce and phase offset, use the following CSS:
css
@keyframes catBounce {
  0%, 100% { transform: translateY(0); }
  50% { transform: translateY(-10px); }
}

.walking-cat {
  animation: catBounce 0.4s alternate infinite ease-in-out;
}

.walking-cat:nth-child(even) {
  animation-delay: 0.2s; /* Phase offset for bounce */
}

This creates a 10px vertical bounce with alternating timing for a chaotic walking effect.

To make a Wikipedia article title scroll dynamically, inject a `<marquee>` tag into the `#firstHeading` element. Here's the JavaScript code:
javascript
var $title = $('#firstHeading');
var titleText = $title.html();
$title.html('<marquee scrollamount="15" behavior="alternate">' + titleText + '</marquee>');

This wraps the title in a scrolling marquee with alternating horizontal movement and a scroll speed of 15.
